{The Queen's Gambit is one of the oldest and most respected openings. White offers a pawn to gain central control.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 {The Queen's Gambit. Not a true gambit — White can almost always regain the pawn.} e6 {The Queen's Gambit Declined — solid and classical.} (2... dxc4 {The Queen's Gambit Accepted. Black takes the pawn but must use tempi to hold it.} 3. Nf3 (3. e4 {The central push — aggressive but allows counterplay.} e5 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Bxc4 Nc6) Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 {Black strikes back in the center immediately.} 6. O-O a6 {Preparing ...b5 to expand on the queenside.} 7. Qe2 b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 {Black has equalized and has active piece play.}) (2... c6 {The Slav Defense — supports d5 without locking in the light-squared bishop.} 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 {The main line Slav.} 5. a4 Bf5 {Black develops the bishop before playing ...e6. This is the key idea of the Slav.} 6. e3 e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 {Active development.}) (2... e5 {The Albin Countergambit — aggressive but risky.} 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 {White holds the extra pawn.}) 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {The Classical QGD. White pins the knight.} Be7 {The Orthodox Defense.} (4... Nbd7 {Preparing to break the pin with ...c6 later.} 5. e3 c6 6. Nf3 Qa5 {The Cambridge Springs Variation — a tricky line.} 7. Nd2 Bb4 8. Qc2 O-O) (4... c5 {The Tarrasch Defense — active but accepts an isolated d-pawn.} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. g3 {The isolated pawn gives Black active pieces but a long-term structural weakness.}) 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 Nbd7 {The tabiya of the Orthodox QGD.} 7. Rc1 {Preparing to pressure the c-file.} c6 8. Bd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd5 {Black has freed the position and stands comfortably.} *
